summary: I always viewed hulk as a separate person from Bruce and Ragnarok really hammered that point in - so Bruce becoming Like That...
body: I always viewed hulk as a separate person from Bruce and Ragnarok really hammered that point in - so Bruce becoming Like That read more to me like Hulk going into a deep depression over his realization that he CAN lose and just- giving up. Letting Bruce have full control because even though Bruce is a puny human, he still tries to fight and Hulk doesn’t understand that but he respects it. Hulks given up and Bruce doesn’t understand that’s what happened because Bruce still hasn’t really ever gotten past his view of Hulk being a ‘rage monster’ instead of a PERSON.

summary:
Okay, I loved Endgame, but I’m gonna talk about a particular scene that kinda bugged me and it was...
This scene ... Oh god I’m...
body:
Okay, I loved Endgame, but I’m gonna talk about a particular scene that kinda bugged me and it was…

This scene … Oh god I’m gonna get murdered


It’s great to see female representation on the big screen, unless if it’s done right. This scene was just forced, and it really bugged me. Here are the reasons why (I only have 2).

1. It was too rushed.

The scene quickly went straight to Point B. Carol comes in, and bumps into Spider-Man. An army of Thanos’ minions start to charge towards them. Peter asks Carol if she’s able to take them down. Then suddenly, all 9 female Superheroes (Gamora, Nebula, Valkyrie, Pepper, Shuri, Okoye, Mantis, Hope, Wanda) enter the scene. That’s A LOT to help the STRONGEST character (Carol) to take down a simple army of Thanos’ minions. To make this scene better, they could’ve gone from Point A, to Point B. Getting one scene, to build up to the next scene, and then the final scene, the 10 female heroes are all in one place. Point A, being something that could result to Point B, the women assembling.

2. They hardly know each other

Gamora and Nebula, hardly know any of them, and with Nebula being someone who needs to trust or know someone’s intentions before going into action with them, it just felt off. Valkyrie hasn’t met anyone one of them, and the same goes to Hope (though she probably seen Wanda or Pepper on the news or something), and Mantis. Pepper who would probably knew Wanda (maybe from AoU or Civil War) and Nebula (from when Tony returns to earth). This ties with my first point.

As I said, it’s great to see female representation in film and shows, but only if it’s done right.

summary:
Okay but you don't understand how deep and meaningful Natasha's sacrifice truly is.
In the Red Room, they were raised to become...
body:
“It was always them or me. And I chose me, every single time.” — Natasha

Okay but you don’t understand how deep and meaningful Natasha’s sacrifice truly is.

In the Red Room, they were raised to become killers, unfeeling of anything but the need for survival (in order to complete their missions properly) no matter the cost. She was able to do things we can’t even imagine because it was drilled into her that it was a life or death matter. If she wanted to live, someone else had to die.

Only when Clint found and spared her did she start seeing things differently, albeit reluctantly at first. And only when she met the Avengers one by one and all of the other people who came into her life and showed her better, did she start to believe that only choosing others and not herself can she make up for the choice she had made, over and over again. And so, starts her journey at S.H.I.E.L.D. until she becomes an Avenger, doing good, no matter the cost.

How many times did she face life and death situations and chose saving others in death over living her life and losing them? So many.

“I’m not saying we should leave,”

“Where else am I gonna get a view like this?”

And then Clint and her arrive in Vormir. And they face, arguably, the biggest life or death situation yet. And to Natasha, it’s the same question all over again. “Them, or you?”

It’s a hard decision, not because she doesn’t want to die but because she wants to live. She wants to go back and see all of her friends, her family, and she wants to be there when they right the wrong that Thanos has done. When they avenge the world and beyond it.

But she has made a promise to herself, and she has set a goal.

It’s not simply “Clint or me?” to her. It’s THEM, the whole universe, versus herself.

And like she promised she would, like she believed is right, like every single time since she left her old way of life – she chose them.

In doing so, she believed that her ledger – “dripping, gushing red” – had been wiped clean. But not because she saved Clint. Not because she saved the world.

But because she didn’t choose herself.

And the question that followed her for her whole life, she finally could answer for the last time. And she thinks she really got it right, this time.

Thank you, Natasha Romanoff. Your soul is the brightest, the greatest, the most beautiful and the world didn’t deserve it as much as you thought it did. You are loved.

“We have what we have when we have it” — Natasha Romanoff

Vitae Summa Brevis Spem Nos Vetat Incohare Longam - The Shortness of Life Forbids Us Long Hopes.

body:
Probably an unpopular opinion

But honestly, I didn’t like Captain Marvel’s character in Endgame, and I didn’t like the scene where all the girls got together to help her get through the enemy gauntlet.

So first, her character. She came across, to me, as a douche. She acted all “I’m more important than everyone because I’m stronger” and I didn’t like it. She’s meant to be someone who was beaten down on for years and finally can live to her potential, so why is she so “I’m better than everyone else”? Didn’t like.

And second, that scene. I understand why it was done, but putting it in that moment didn’t work for me. Everyone, literally everyone, wants to see that glove get where it needs to be, away from Thanos, so why is it only the girls coming to help? Doesn’t make sense.

No, I’m not complaining about having a scene of kick-ass girls going “we got this” I’m complaining about its position in the film. (With Captain Marvel, I am complaining about her being in like four scenes and being badly written in all… One of my friend’s said maybe she was written in late… Which would explain the scarcity, but not the bad charactering).
